    "projects": [
        {
            "title": "Process design for the recovery of polyphenols from green tea using macroporous resins",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 2,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2014
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 2,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2014
                }
            },
            "description": "In this study, a process is designed for the separation and purification of catechins (polyphenols)\npresent in green tea, which have several claimed health benefits. For this purpose,\nsolvent swing adsorption using polymeric resins is employed, and 2 resins (Amberlite\nXAD7HP and Diaion HP-20) are studied for their applicability in this process. The solvent\nused during adsorption is water and for desorption a water-ethanol mixture is employed.\nA mathematical model based on one dimensional axial plug flow is developed to simulate\nthe dynamics of the adsorption column. The model parameters are regressed from experimental\ndata. This is used to design the solvent swing adsorption column, with optimized\noperating parameters for a high yield of catechins.",
